'''iCAM''' is a [[color appearance model]] developed by [[Mark D. Fairchild]] and [[Garrett M. Johnson]] that was published in 2002 at the IS&T/SID 10th Color Imaging Conference in [[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]].<ref name="refMunsellWebsite">{{cite web | author=Munsell Color Science Laboratory Website Content Author | title=iCAM: An Image Appearance Model | publisher=Munsell Color Science Laboratory | year=2009 | url=http://www.cis.rit.edu/mcsl/iCAM/}}</ref>
It has been recognized that there are significant aspects of color appearance phenomena that are not described well, if at all, by models such as [[CIECAM97s]] or [[CIECAM02]].<ref name="refMeetICamPaper">{{cite journal | author=Mark D. Fairchild, Garrett M. Johnson | title=Meet iCAM: A Next-Generation Color Appearance Model | year=2002}}</ref>
The requirements for such a model include<ref name=refMeetICamPaper/> * Simple implementation for images * Spatially localized adaptation and [[tone mapping]] for [[High dynamic range imaging|high-dynamic-range images]] * Other [[Spatial analysis|spatial phenomena]] * Accurate [[Color|color appearance]] * Scales for [[gamut mapping]] and other image editing procedures * [[Spatial filtering]] for visibility of artifacts * [[Color difference]] metrics for image quality assessment
